16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 200 of Title 75A, unless there
19 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Oklahoma AI
21 Education Innovation Act".
22 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 201 of Title 75A, unless there
24 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 A. There is hereby created in the State Treasury a revolving
2 fund to be designated the "Oklahoma AI Education Innovation
3 Revolving Fund". The fund shall be a continuing fund, not subject
4 to fiscal year limitations, and shall consist of:
5 1. All monies appropriated to the fund by the Legislature;
6 2. All monies received from gifts, grants, reimbursements, or
7 other contributions from public or private sources for purposes
8 consistent with this act;
9 3. Any interest or investment earnings attributable to monies
10 in the fund; and
11 4. Any other monies designated for deposit in the fund.
12 B. All monies accruing to the credit of the Oklahoma AI
13 Education Innovation Revolving Fund are hereby appropriated and
14 shall be budgeted and distributed by the Office of Management and
15 Enterprise Services as follows:
16 1. Forty-two and two-tenths percent (42.2%) to the State
17 Department of Education;
18 2. Forty-two and two-tenths percent (42.2%) to the Oklahoma
19 State Regents for Higher Education;
20 3. Eight and nine-tenths percent (8.9%) to the Oklahoma
21 Department of Career and Technology Education; and
22 4. Six and seven-tenths percent (6.7%) to the Oklahoma
23 Department of Libraries.
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 C. Distributions from the fund shall be made quarterly,
2 beginning on the first day of the fiscal quarter following the
3 effective date of this act, and on the first day of each fiscal
4 quarter thereafter. The Office of Management and Enterprise
5 Services shall transfer the amounts specified in subsection B of
6 this section to each designated agency within ten (10) business days
7 of the beginning of each fiscal quarter.
8 D. Monies distributed from the Oklahoma AI Education Innovation
9 Revolving Fund shall be expended by the receiving agencies solely
10 for one or more of the following purposes related to artificial
11 intelligence in education:
12 1. Development, acquisition, and implementation of artificial
13 intelligence tools, platforms, and resources for educational use;
14 2. Professional development and training for educators,
15 administrators, librarians, and staff on the effective and ethical
16 use of artificial intelligence in educational settings;
17 3. Curriculum development integrating artificial intelligence
18 concepts, digital literacy, and computational thinking;
19 4. Research and evaluation of artificial intelligence
20 applications in education;
21 5. Student programs and initiatives promoting artificial
22 intelligence literacy and workforce readiness;
23 6. Infrastructure improvements necessary to support artificial
24 intelligence educational initiatives;
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 7. Public awareness and community education programs regarding
2 artificial intelligence; and
3 8. Administrative costs directly related to the purposes
4 enumerated in this subsection, provided that no more than five
5 percent (5%) of any agency's annual distribution may be expended for
6 administrative costs.
7 E. Monies in the Oklahoma AI Education Innovation Revolving
8 Fund, and monies distributed therefrom to the agencies designated in
9 subsection B of this section, shall be used solely for the purposes
10 specified in subsection D of this section and for no other purpose
11 whatsoever. Any appropriation, transfer, expenditure, or use of any
12 monies in the fund or distributed from the fund for any purpose not
13 authorized by subsection D of this section shall be null and void
14 and of no effect.
15 F. Monies distributed from the fund to the agencies designated
16 in subsection B of this section that are not expended during a
17 fiscal year shall not revert to the fund or to the General Revenue
18 Fund but shall be retained by the receiving agency and shall remain
19 available for expenditure in subsequent fiscal years for the
20 purposes specified in subsection D of this section.
21 G. No later than October 1 of each year, each agency receiving
22 monies from the Oklahoma AI Education Innovation Revolving Fund
23 shall submit a report to the Governor, the President Pro Tempore of
24 the Oklahoma State Senate, the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 4
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 Repr esentatives, and the Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council
2 detailing:
3 1. The total amount of monies received from the fund during the
4 preceding fiscal year;
5 2. A detailed accounting of all expenditures made from such
6 monies, organized by the purpose categories specified in subsection
7 D of this section;
8 3. The educational outcomes achieved through such expenditures;
9 4. Any unexpended balances and the intended use of such
10 balances; and
11 5. Recommended improvements or modifications to the agency's
12 artificial intelligence education initiatives.
13 H. The State Treasurer shall maintain separate accounts within
14 the Oklahoma AI Education Innovation Revolving Fund sufficient to
15 track deposits, distributions, and balances attributable to each
16 funding source.
17 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 202 of Title 75A, unless there
19 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 A. There is hereby created, to continue until July 1, 2031, in
21 accordance with the provisions of the Oklahoma Sunset Law, the
22 Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council.
23 B. The Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council shall consist of
24 seventeen (17) members as follows:
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 5
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 1. The State Superintendent of Public Instruction, or designee;
2 2. The Chancellor of the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
3 Education, or designee;
4 3. The State Director of the Oklahoma Department of Career and
5 Technology Education, or designee;
6 4. The Director of the Oklahoma Department of Libraries, or
7 designee;
8 5. One member appointed by the Governor with experience in
9 artificial intelligence research or development;
10 6. One member appointed by the Governor with experience in K-12
11 education;
12 7. One member appointed by the Governor with experience in
13 workforce development;
14 8. One member appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the
15 Senate with experience in higher education;
16 9. One member appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the
17 Senate with experience in educational technology;
18 10. One member appointed by the Speaker of the House of
19 Representatives with experience in business or industry utilizing
20 artificial intelligence;
21 11. One member appointed by the Speaker of the House of
22 Representatives with experience in rural education;
23
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 6
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 12. One member who is a current classroom teacher, appointed
2 jointly by the State Superintendent of Public Instruction and the
3 Chancellor of the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education;
4 13. One member who is a current public school administrator,
5 appointed by the State Superintendent of Public Instruction;
6 14. One member who is a current faculty member at an
7 institution within The Oklahoma State System of Higher Education,
8 appointed by the Chancellor of the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
9 Education;
10 15. One member representing Oklahoma tribal nations with
11 interest in educational technology, appointed by the Governor in
12 consultation with the Oklahoma Indian Affairs Commission;
13 16. One member who is a current student enrolled in a public
14 high school or institution of higher education in Oklahoma,
15 appointed jointly by the Speaker of the House of Representatives and
16 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate; and
17 17. One member representing the Oklahoma business community,
18 appointed by the Governor.
19 C. 1. The four ex officio members designated in paragraphs 1
20 through 4 of subsection B of this section shall serve for the
21 duration of their terms of office.
22 2. Appointed members shall serve for terms of three (3) years
23 and may be reappointed for one additional term.
24 3. Initial appointments shall be staggered as follows:
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 7
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 a. members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 5, 8, 10, 12,
2 and 15 of subsection B of this section shall serve
3 initial terms of three (3) years,
4 b. members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 6, 9, 11, 13,
5 and 16 of subsection B of this section shall serve
6 initial terms of two (2) years, and
7 c. members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 7, 14, and 17
8 of subsection B of this section shall serve initial
9 terms of one (1) year.
10 4. Vacancies shall be filled for the unexpired term in the same
11 manner as the original appointment.
12 5. Any member may be removed by the appointing authority for
13 cause.
14 D. Members of the Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council shall
15 be exempt from the dual-office-holding prohibitions of Section 6 of
16 Title 51 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
17 E. Members of the Council shall receive no compensation for
18 their service but shall be reimbursed for necessary travel expenses
19 incurred in the performance of their duties in accordance with the
20 State Travel Reimbursement Act.
21 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 203 of Title 75A, unless there
23 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 8
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 A. The Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council shall have the
2 following powers and duties:
3 1. Advise and make recommendations to the State Department of
4 Education, the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education, the
5 Oklahoma Department of Career and Technology Education, and the
6 Oklahoma Department of Libraries on matters relating to:
7 a. the development and implementation of artificial
8 intelligence education initiatives,
9 b. coordination among agencies to maximize the
10 effectiveness of artificial intelligence education
11 investments,
12 c. best practices for integrating artificial intelligence
13 into curriculum and instruction,
14 d. ethical considerations and responsible use of
15 artificial intelligence in educational settings,
16 e. workforce preparation for careers involving artificial
17 intelligence, and
18 f. digital literacy and equitable access to artificial
19 intelligence educational resources;
20 2. Review the annual reports submitted by agencies pursuant to
21 Section 2 of this act and provide feedback and recommendations;
22 3. Identify gaps, redundancies, or opportunities for
23 collaboration among agencies receiving monies from the Oklahoma AI
24 Education Innovation Revolving Fund;
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 9
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 4. Monitor national and international trends in artificial
2 intelligence education and make recommendations for Oklahoma to
3 remain competitive;
4 5. Engage with stakeholders including educators, students,
5 parents, employers, and community members to gather input on
6 artificial intelligence education needs and priorities;
7 6. Develop and recommend metrics for evaluating the
8 effectiveness of artificial intelligence education initiatives
9 funded through the Oklahoma AI Education Innovation Revolving Fund;
10 and
11 7. Perform such other advisory duties as may be requested by
12 the Governor, the Legislature, or the agencies receiving monies from
13 the fund.
14 B. The Council shall have no authority to direct, control, or
15 supervise the operations of any state agency, institution, or school
16 district. All recommendations of the Council shall be advisory only
17 and shall not be binding on any agency or institution.
18 C. No later than December 1 of each year, the Council shall
19 submit an annual report to the Governor, the President Pro Tempore
20 of the Senate, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, the
21 State Board of Education, and the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
22 Education. The report shall include:
23 1. A summary of Council activities during the preceding year;
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 10
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 2. An assessment of the progress of artificial intelligence
2 education initiatives across all receiving agencies;
3 3. Findings and recommendations for improving coordination and
4 effectiveness;
5 4. Identification of emerging opportunities or challenges in
6 artificial intelligence education; and
7 5. Any recommended legislative or administrative actions.
8 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 204 of Title 75A, unless there
10 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 A. The Oklahoma AI Education Advisory Council shall meet at
12 least quarterly at the call of the chair. Additional meetings may
13 be called by the chair, or upon written request of a majority of the
14 members.
15 B. At its first meeting, the Council shall elect from among its
16 members a chair and a vice-chair who shall serve for terms of two
17 (2) years. The chair and vice-chair may be reelected.
18 C. A majority of the members of the Council shall constitute a
19 quorum for the transaction of business. All official actions of the
20 Council shall require the affirmative vote of a majority of those
21 members present and voting.
22 D. The Council may establish subcommittees as it deems
23 necessary to carry out its duties. Subcommittees may include
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB1782 SFLR Page 11
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 indi viduals who are not members of the Council, provided that such
2 individuals shall serve in a nonvoting advisory capacity.
3 E. All meetings of the Council and its subcommittees shall be
4 subject to the Oklahoma Open Meeting Act.
5 F. The State Department of Education, the Oklahoma State
6 Regents for Higher Education, the Oklahoma Department of Career and
7 Technology Education, and the Oklahoma Department of Libraries shall
8 provide staff support, information, and assistance to the Council as
9 requested. The agencies may designate staff to serve jointly as
10 support for the Council and may share the costs of such support
11 proportionally based on the distribution percentages specified in
12 Section 1 of this act.
13 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 205 of Title 75A, unless there
15 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 If any provision of this act or the application thereof to any
17 person or circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity shall not
18 affect other provisions or applications of the act which can be
19 given effect without the invalid provision or application, and to
20 this end the provisions of this act are declared to be severable.
21 SECTION 7. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
22 COMMITTEE REPORT BY: COMMITTEE ON TECHNOLOGY AND TELECOMMUNICATIONS
